lineage I got these DATs from Dougal about 3-3.5 years ago.  I had mentioned on some other group that I was trying to find the best possible copy of this show to vine to the masses.  I got a private email telling me to send two 60m DATs and I'd be hooked up.  Well when I got the DATs and saw the lineage written on the cases I about flipped ! So I set to mastering these on CD. the mastering was as follows:

Panasonic sv-3700 > Cool Edit Pro via SPDIF > CD Wave > CD/SHN

and I sent a copy of this off to Mike Hall to be vined and the rest is history - that's the story of how this show came to me and then on into public circulation.

What a wonderful show and what a treat to be able to sit here and stream the show....
Thanks Dougal !
enjoy!

top 5! Well 1973 is a year where it's almost impossible to pick a top 5, even a top 10. But this show just shines!Only the 2nd show of the year, and when it's this good, you know the rest of the year is gonna be special-it was! A "greatest hits" first set that pleases everyone. And the 2nd Set opener HC Sunshine may be the best ever- Jerry wails! The  Dark Star is one of the best for 1973- very jazzy and mellow, with a magical transition into Eyes. Phil also is beginning to come into his own now as a soloist, as you'll hear. One of the first monster Phil shows of 1973. An auspicious portend of the year's musical heights that lay ahead. Plus Uncle John's Band for an encore? Get outta here!
Enjoy this show with your favorite cereal.

I think this was the second (or third?) Eyes, and it already sounds classic. China Doll here is brilliant as well.

Desert Island 73 If I could only take 3 73 shows with me, this, 11-11, and 12-12 would be it.  Yes, even above the RFK and Kezar shows.  All of my favorites feature excellent Eyes, but this one--the second one played--has been one of my favorites for nearly 20 years.  Starts off with a great Phil solo out of Dark Star, and just a sublime, relaxed intro into Eyes--it's picks up steam like an old steam engine.  Complete with the harmonics concurrent with the end of Phil's solo, it will blow you away.

Jerry's solos would not get this back to this level until the fall, imho.  The exit jam is equally compelling, and lengthy, and falls perfectly into China Doll.  Add to that a crushing HC Sunshine, a wonderfully long PITB in the first set, and some stellar versions of Bertha, Big River, Jed, Straw, and China>Rider (this was one of the last pre-retirement China>Riders without the little UJB-like riff before Rider), and incredible sound quality...well, why haven't you downloaded it yet??

Great show, sound not that good though I'd definitely give this a 5+ star rating based soley on the band's performance. It's strong and the show is long. Check out the Eyes Of The World, it's completely off the hook. However the recording has some noticable volume fluctuations, two cut songs and often the sound is kinda grainy. Everything is audible but clarity is lost due to what I can only describe as a grimy/gritty element to the sound. It's not clipping, just not clear. But don't let that stop you from streaming this wonderful show, it's absolutely worth hearing and the sound issues aren't that bad. 1973 seems to get short shrift or doesn't get praised enough and I don't know why. Maybe because '72 was so completely innovative and '74 was so stellar in the jam department? Well 1973 was kind of a transitional year but even an average show from '73 is wonderful and this show is above average. I was just beginning to explore the '73 stuff when Archive changed their policy about downloads, this is one of the few shows I got:-(   I wish there was some way to convince the Dead that downloading is a good thing. I also noticed that the incredible 11/17/73 Pauley Pavillion show is completely gone, is it going to be commercially released? It should be.

What else can be said? I got the .shn of this board just before that deal went down as an upgrade for one of the earliest shows I got, which I wore out in my youth.  I agree the overall mix is fantastic, though the VBR sounds a bit less clean to my ear (A- maybe).  

The highlights are many, including a great TLEO (they should've kept the bridge and not slowed it down, I feel these early '73 versions are the better arrangement), some of Jerry's best chicken pickin' in Big River, an afore-mentioned killer Bertha, my 2nd favorite Here Comes Sunshine (just edged out by DP#1), a nice China>Rider, and of course the dreamy, jazzy Dark Star>Eyes>China Doll centerpiece.  A word about the Eyes: Yeah, it's not fully developed, and they don't flow through the outro changes as well as in subsequent years, but the spacey, almost meandering quality of this Eyes jam is a PERFECT compliment to both the spartan 'Star before it, and the delicate China Doll after it.  Listen with an open mind, and try not to compare to some of the obviously tighter Eyes.

'73 is my personal favorite year for the boys, you've got that great '72 intensity and edge, a bunch of new (soon to be classic) songs that haven't become old for them yet, and the first glimpse of the more improvisationally tight '74 style.

Not to put down any other section of this classic show, but that "moment" really makes the show for me.

The Wheel Actually, your instincts were right on, as The Wheel appeared on Garcia's first solo album, recorded in 1971. It's not unusual to hear familier phrases of music in Dark Star jams, it seems a place they go to work things out.

The ride began As an 18 yr old UW freshmen, this was my first show. I still remember the wild, ecstatic look on a friends face as Casey Jones ended the 1st set. Zabriskie Point The much-acclaimed solo between Dark Star and Eyes of the World reminds me a lot of the song that Jerry did for the love scene in the movie Zabriskie Point, which came out in 1970.  That's one of my favorite songs in any category, so it was pretty cool to hear in this show, even just partially.

OUTRAGEOUSLY GOOD SHOW!!!! I have a tape everything after HCS, but the order had to be ammended because of the length of the DS>EYES>CHINA DOLL, which was all of side 2, with the other songs making up side 1.   It's great to be able to hear the 1st set though.   The DARK STAR has to be in my top 3 DS's ever.   I can still remember being BLOWN AWAY listening to this show for the 1st time.   Some have said that the early Eyes post-lyrics-jams weren't all that great---I BEG TO DIFFER!!!   While it does seem a little subdued when compared to what the jam morphed into, it seems to fit just perfectly in the context of the show & the seque it is part of.

I've also wanted to know what the loud "POP" is about 2/3 of the way through Dark Star.   On my tape it was a little clearer-sounding that what's on this recording.   Anyway, this show is in my top 5 of all time.   Remember though, we all hear things just a little differently---it's ALL in how the music makes YOU feel.

excellence An exquisite performance, that must rank among the best of the year. No flubs, top-notch sound, and a dreamy set list. 

Almost every tune is a highlight, but pay attention to the following: "Box" for the band's fab harmony, "China>Rider's" passion, "Playin's" deep improvised journey, "You Ain't Woman Enough" (go Donna, for a change!), "TLEO's" funky bopping melody, and the entire "Dark Star>Eyes>China Doll" sequence for it's rich and varying soundscapes catapulted by Phil's  bass solo that bridges "Star" and "Eyes."

This is an excellent example of why we love this band.

Here Comes Sunshine Defined immaculate grateful dead music. this is not a great recording, but immensely enjoyable in any form because of an incredible exhibition of confidence on the part of the band which makes for an all time keeper performance. this is balls out 1973 progressive rock. I had attended the Maples show a week prior and that was a rock fest.

The version of HC Sunshine is so over the top, far ranging yet but gathering in, it would be hard to discern the album cut over it, but because of its intendant jam it just goes into the exact areas we never thought possible. Thereby, the unexpected frees the soul.

As I am listening to Dark Star, outside my window, municipal fireworks go off adding their flash  into the conflagration of a tepid evening sky. The finishing touch is a decapitating Phil solo that leads into a hint of the same chording that graces HC Sunshine/Midnight Hour and floods the night with Eyes.

When by 1977 they would have quickly ended with a few more songs, the Dead pile-drive right into almost like a third set without taking a break. And every square or round inch of it is impeccably played while holding onto the muse's hand of forthright, yet gracious, improv. 

A jammed-to-the-max Eyes lends itself to Mind Left
and cascading down Everest finely links back up with the trail and into China Doll. This version acts as a bit of a rest period for the three guitarists. And then they kick royal ass throughout the rest of the show.

First There Was A Rider Then There Was No Rider Then There Was It took me a while to find it but I knew Jerry must have thought of it at some point.

There's a band I played in for a while years ago and we used to have a lot of fun with the jam between China and Rider.  Yes, the usual UJB tweak to be sure but one day outta no-where we took it way way down and slurried it around a bit and out spooged Mountain Jam ala Allmans based on the old Donovan song.  It became a best loved spacey love sluice in the middle of China-Rider and oft times prompted an Über snurfish Rider out the back end.

"WHY IS HE WRITING THIS LOAD OF SPEW!?!?"

Well, kids, check out this tiny little noodle Jerry drops in just before the first verse of Rider.  Mountain Jam to be sure.  The way it's phrased, it has the feel of something he literally stumbled upon and then seems to have quickly had the thought, "Hmm, think I save that for later".

I don't fer sure know if they ever opted to develop that into anything, but for a tiny moment, there it was.  

Great minds DO think alike.  {:>)

When in doubt, tune up.

Here are a few more thoughts I have while listening to this song:

I feel like I'm caught on the ripple of a pond from a freshly thrown stone... up and down I go with reverberations and echoes ringing in my head until what I thought was infinity is casually reunited with the present reality.

You have to listen in the right frame of mind and analyze the consciousness/madness.

Dark Star is inventive and unanticipated. I think it is largely due to Billy or Mickey's rat-a-tat-tat on the symbols. Ting-tang-ting they ring. And then Phil took it along a journey through the woods up and down winding paths (Even made me get up and move closer to the other "phil side" speaker).

Like sliding down the back of a penguin...

The "Eyes of the World" seems like it collapses. A bunch of people standing around a sink whole saying, "Where did the the sound go?" and then, as it begins to swirl like quicksand in an hour glass, it erupts out into a volcanic jam with smooth veins of hot lava meandering down the mountain into a pool which is called, "China Doll." Lava is funny. you can see it coming a mile away. It moves quite slowly. But as it burns and keeps away the yearning of such turning away.  The China Doll could be felt through the whole jam! It wails like a calling from a far away stable... calling the horses home. Consider the following lines:
"All I leave behind me is only what I found"
and
"Take up your china doll, take up your china doll,
it's only fractured and just a little nervous from the fall."

With the coolest, cool down... My darlin' Sugaree! Just don't tell them that you know of me.

-TDT

The review sections lately I know that this post completely does exactly what it's addressing, but I notice a lot of people writing reviews about what other people write reviews about. The review section really pops out at you on this website, so I think that it's easy to become focused on it, and the review section is starting to lose the spirit of what it's meant for because of the focus on it. It's probably not something that's on the top of archive.org's list of things to change, but this is just a shout out and suggestion for us that we bring back the purpose of the review section and put the value back on writing solid reviews specifically about the performance, production quality, or anything at all that isn't bickering between reviews or making generalized statements about the other reviews written here.  This review probably seemed a little cunty... and technically hypocritical. But I am willing to wager that you, like me, would love to read a review section with more reviews on the music and upload than reviews on reviews.

Reunited with a long lost friend! Driving up to college from NYC for the start of my freshman year in the Boston area in August, 1989, my Mom and I stopped off at a cousin's house in Providence to spend the night.
She was already off at school, so I stayed in her room and, out of curiosity, perused her cassette collection.
I was a fairly recent (but passionately deadicated) convert to the Dead nation and hadn't realized that this older cousin of mine was herself a major Dead Head.
Randomly picked out a bootleg labeled "Madison, '73" and listened to and copied it that night.  
I think it was the first time I ever heard They Love Each Other.  
From there to Dark Star --> Eyes and I was a total goner.
This quickly became one of my closest companions alongside Barton Hall '77 (my very first bootleg) in my small but high-quality (that's music quality, not sound quality) collection.
Anyway, a year later I dropped out of college to study Talmud in yeshiva over seas and I put away my Dead collection for about a decade and a half.
Fast forward another 10 years or so and I'm an occasional visitor here to get a fix every now and then.
Never did find my old Madison '73 again and with shows today labeled by venue name had no idea how to reconnect to that old friend from long ago.
Opened up Archive this morning and randomly selected this one to keep me company over a leisurely breakfast.
Was enjoying the groove but not paying particularly close attention...until, that is, we started to enter the Phil Zone at about the 16:00 mark in Dark Star.
At 17:00 (and then Jerry's re-entrance at 18:30) that sound is so uniquely melodic I knew I had finally found it!
With a deep listening to Eyes I was in love all over again.
